  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Hebrews 13:1-2",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Hebrews 13:1-2",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In this concluding chapter we find fresh instances of that divine wisdom wherewith the apostle was influenced in writing this epistle; improving still more the doctrines he had advanced to practical purposes; in which he gives all ministers of Christ an instructive example of the order and method proper to be pursued in teaching Christianity; first to declare the great doctrines of it, and then to improve them to promote holiness. And they will be mistaken who propose to themselves any other method, and those most of all who think one part of it is sufficient without the other.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Let brotherly love continue ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Or abide constant. Love is the fountain and foundation of all moral and religious duties which Christians owe to each other and to all men, and therefore it is here placed at the head of them all. Several of the fruits of this love are touched on in the following verses. It is justly observed by Diodati, that this exhortation was peculiarly suitable to the converted Jews, as the prejudices of many of them against their Gentile brethren were so strong that they were ready to disown them with abhorrence. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Be not forgetful to entertain strangers ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The apostle chiefly means those of their Christian brethren who were travelling from place to place at their own cost to preach the gospel. Thus St. John speaks of some who ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "went forth for the sake of Christ, taking nothing of the Gentiles, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "to whom they preached, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "3 John 1:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Add to this, the church being then under great persecution in sundry places, many Christians were obliged to leave their own habitations and countries, and to flee for safety to other parts where they were strangers. Such as these the apostle recommends to the love and charity of those to whom he wrote. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For thereby some ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— For instance, Abraham and Lot; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "have entertained angels unawares ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— So may an unknown guest, even now, be of more worth than he appears, and may have angels attending him, though unseen.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
